\title[A Resolution Framework]{A Resolution Framework for Finite-Sample Model Selection}

\author{Yaoping Wang}
\affil{Department of Statistics, Rutgers University, Piscataway, NJ, USA}
\email{yw1580@scarletmail.rutgers.edu}

\abstract{The ML community selects models using finite validation sets, often at budgets where classical statistics predicts that rankings cannot be resolved. This paper proposes a pre-experimental diagnostic protocol to determine whether the evaluation budget can support statistically distinguishable comparisons. The protocol centers on $\Delta_{\min}$, a resolution threshold derived from the two-proportion $z$-test. It embeds a formal decision rule (Decision Rule~1): when the observed performance range falls below $\Delta_{\min}$, uniform model averaging (soup) minimizes expected regret; when it exceeds $\Delta_{\min}$, argmax is preferable. We validate the protocol on Qwen2.5-7B and Mistral-7B across multiple seeds, scales, and training paradigms. At full GSM8K ($N=1319$), $\Delta_{\min}=3.8$~pp exceeds the observed checkpoint range of $3.0$~pp. Crucially, the protocol does not uniformly predict failure: for Mistral-7B at $N=200$, $\Delta_{\min}=8.11$~pp is exceeded by the $10.5$~pp observed range. The decision rule selects soup across all three Qwen seeds (consistent) and argmax for Mistral (consistent). Bootstrap, Monte Carlo calibration, and continuous-metric extension (cross-entropy loss variance $0.18$, $\Delta_{\min}\approx0.06$) further support the framework. A quick-reference table and a catalog of nine pitfalls accompany the protocol; an exploratory survey of 36 papers (78 claims) finds that $71\%$ of claimed improvements fall below $\Delta_{\min}$.}

\keywords{Model selection, evaluation budget, statistical resolution, $\Delta_{\min}$, fine-tuning, reproducibility}

