\section{Limitations}\label{sec:limitations}
% ============================================================

All experiments use two model families (Qwen2.5 and Mistral-7B), a single training regime (LoRA, 500 steps), and two task types (GSM8K, MMLU). The $\Delta_{\min}$ pattern replicates across seeds, scales, training paradigms, and architectures. Broader claims require broader experimentation. The Mistral-7B discriminative check is based on a single training seed. Multi-seed replication would strengthen this claim. The continuous metric extension (Appendix~\ref{app:continuous}) uses the Delta method under a normality assumption. For heavy-tailed loss distributions, bootstrap-based variance estimation may be more appropriate. The literature survey is a convenience sample and should not be interpreted as a systematic meta-analysis.

% ============================================================
\section{Conclusion}\label{sec:conclusion}
% ============================================================

We proposed and validated $\Delta_{\min}$ as a pre-flight diagnostic for model selection: before asking which model is best, first ask whether the evaluation budget can tell the difference. The protocol requires only $N$ and $\bar{p}$ (defaulting to $\bar{p}=0.5$ when unknown) and returns a threshold that determines whether observed performance gaps exceed the noise floor.

The most instructive finding is the divergence between Qwen2.5-7B and Mistral-7B at the same budget ($N=200$): $\Delta_{\min}=9.8$~pp exceeds the Qwen range of $8.0$~pp, while $\Delta_{\min}=8.11$~pp falls below the Mistral range of $10.5$~pp. This discriminative validity, that the framework correctly identifies one configuration as resolvable and another as not, is the strongest evidence that $\Delta_{\min}$ captures genuine resolution constraints rather than uniformly classifying all comparisons as noise. Bootstrap, power-curve calibration, and paired-vs.-independent comparisons (Appendix~\ref{app:paired}) further support the threshold's interpretation. A survey of 36 recent papers (78 claims) finds that 71\% of reported improvements fall below the resolution threshold implied by their budgets. The problem is not unique to our experiments.

We recommend that $\Delta_{\min}$ computation become a standard submission checkpoint for any benchmark evaluation, alongside the release of an open-source implementation. The quick-reference table (Table~\ref{tab:delta_min}), power-curve calibration (Figure~\ref{fig:power_curve}), and diagnostic pitfall catalog (Section~\ref{sec:pitfalls}) are intended as actionable resources for practitioners and reviewers alike.

